%N A386609 Smallest exponent b >= 2 such that the absolute value of the alternating 2-digit block sum of n^b equals n, or 0 if no such b exists.
%C A386609 Let S_2(x) be the absolute value of the alternating sum of base-100 digits of x.
%C A386609 Define a(n) as the smallest b >= 2 with S_2(n^b) = n; if no such b exists, set a(n) = 0.
%C A386609 The sequence seems to exist for all n except powers of 100, for which S_2(100^b) = 1 for all b.
%H A386609 Pieter Post, <a href="/A386609/b386609.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..1000</a>
%F A386609 a(n) = min_{b >= 2 | S_2(n^b) = n} or 0 if no such b exists, where S_2(x) = abs(Sum_{k>=0} (-1)^k * d_k), where x = Sum_{k>=0} d_k * 100^k, 0 <= d_k < 100.
%F A386609 a(100^k) = 0 for k > 0.
%e A386609 a(10) = 3 since 10^3 = 1000 => |10 - 0| = 10.
%e A386609 a(14) = 6 since 14^6 = 7529536 => |7 - 52 + 95 - 36| = 14.
%e A386609 a(91) = 5 since 91^5 = 6240321451 => |62 - 40 + 32 - 14 + 51| = 91.
%o A386609 (Python)
%o A386609 from itertools import count
%o A386609 from sympy.ntheory import digits
%o A386609 def a(n):
%o A386609     if n > 1 and (s:=str(n)) == '1'+'0'*(len(s)//2*2): return 0
%o A386609     return next(b for b in count(2) if n==abs(sum(-d if i&1 else d for i, d in enumerate(map(int, digits(n**b, 100)[1:])))))
%o A386609 print([a(n) for n in range(65)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Oct 25 2025
